# Incident Response — Full Learning Note

## What Is Incident Response?

Incident Response is the structured process of detecting, containing,
investigating, and recovering from a security incident. An incident is
any event that threatens the confidentiality, integrity, or availability
of a system or its data — ransomware, unauthorized access, data
exfiltration, insider threat, malware infection.

The goal of IR is not just to stop the attack. It is to:
- Understand exactly what happened and how
- Preserve evidence before it disappears
- Remove the threat completely
- Prevent recurrence
- Document everything


## The PICERL Framework

Every IR follows this lifecycle. Skip a phase and you'll regret it.

PREPARATION
Before any incident occurs. This is your foundation.
- Define what an "incident" is for your organization
- Build playbooks for common scenarios (ransomware, phishing, insider threat)
- Set up logging and monitoring so you have data to work with
- Know your escalation path and who to contact
- Have your tools ready before you need them

IDENTIFICATION
Something triggered. Determine: real incident or false positive?
- Gather initial indicators — logs, alerts, user reports
- Correlate events across systems — one weird log is noise,
  the same entry across ten machines is signal
- Determine scope — what systems are affected?
- Assign severity — how bad is this?
- Declare the incident so the response clock starts

CONTAINMENT
Stop the bleeding. Do not let it spread.
- Short-term: kill the process, block the IP, lock the account
- Long-term: isolate the affected system from the network entirely
- Critical rule: NEVER eradicate before collecting evidence.
  Containment preserves the crime scene. Eradication cleans it.

ERADICATION
Remove the threat completely.
- Delete malware and all its components
- Remove backdoors, rogue accounts, malicious scheduled tasks
- Patch the exploited vulnerability
- Identify root cause first — if you don't know how they got in,
  you can't be sure you've removed everything

RECOVERY
Restore systems to normal operation.
- Rebuild from clean backups or known-good images where possible
- Monitor closely post-recovery — attackers leave secondary persistence
- Confirm the threat is gone before declaring the incident closed

LESSONS LEARNED
The phase most people skip. Don't.
- Write the post-incident report within 72 hours
- What happened? How? What did you miss? What would have caught it earlier?
- Update playbooks, detection rules, and monitoring accordingly


## Key Concepts

ORDER OF VOLATILITY
Collect evidence in this order — most volatile first:
RAM → Swap/Pagefile → Running Processes → Network Connections → Open Files → Disk

RAM disappears the moment power is cut. Disk survives indefinitely.
Always collect in volatility order or you lose evidence before you
know you needed it.

CHAIN OF CUSTODY
Every piece of evidence must be:
- Hashed (SHA256) immediately upon collection
- Documented every time it is accessed or transferred
- Stored in a way that prevents tampering

If the hash changes at any point, the evidence is compromised.

TRUE POSITIVE VS FALSE POSITIVE
A true positive is a real attack.
A false positive is legitimate activity that looks suspicious.
Telling them apart quickly is the core L1 SOC analyst skill.
Bad triage wastes hours chasing ghosts — or worse, ignoring real incidents.


## Linux IR in Practice

WHERE YOUR EVIDENCE LIVES

/var/log/auth.log       — all logins, SSH sessions, sudo commands
/var/log/syslog         — general system events
/tmp /var/tmp /dev/shm  — attacker drop zones, world-writable
/etc/crontab            — scheduled tasks, classic persistence location
/etc/passwd /etc/shadow — user accounts, look for unexpected additions
~/.bash_history         — command history, attackers often wipe this
/proc/                  — live kernel data, disappears on reboot


## Identification Commands

# Who is logged in right now?
w
who
last -n 20

# Full process tree with parent-child relationships
ps auxf

# All network connections with the process behind them
ss -tulnp
ss -antp

# Suspicious files in attacker-favourite locations
find /tmp /var/tmp /dev/shm -type f -ls 2>/dev/null

# Files modified in the last 24 hours
find / -mtime -1 -type f 2>/dev/null | grep -v proc

# Cron jobs — current user and system-wide
crontab -l
cat /etc/crontab
ls -la /etc/cron.*

# All open files and the processes holding them
sudo lsof


## Containment Commands

# Kill a malicious process (get PID from ps auxf first)
kill -9 <PID>

# Block a malicious IP
sudo iptables -A INPUT -s <IP> -j DROP
sudo iptables -A OUTPUT -d <IP> -j DROP
sudo iptables -L -n -v

# Take a network interface offline
sudo ip link set eth0 down

# Lock a compromised user account
sudo usermod -L <username>
sudo passwd -l <username>


## Evidence Collection Commands

--- RAM Acquisition ---

sudo apt install build-essential linux-headers-$(uname -r) -y
git clone https://github.com/504ensicsLabs/LiME.git
cd LiME/src && make
sudo insmod lime-$(uname -r).ko "path=/home/frost/evidence/ram.lime format=lime"
sha256sum /home/frost/evidence/ram.lime > /home/frost/evidence/ram.lime.sha256

--- Volatile State Capture ---

mkdir -p ~/evidence/volatile

ps auxf > ~/evidence/volatile/processes.txt
ss -antp > ~/evidence/volatile/connections.txt
netstat -rn > ~/evidence/volatile/routing.txt
w > ~/evidence/volatile/users.txt
last -n 50 > ~/evidence/volatile/login_history.txt
sudo lsof > ~/evidence/volatile/open_files.txt
cat /proc/*/cmdline 2>/dev/null | strings > ~/evidence/volatile/cmdlines.txt
sha256sum ~/evidence/volatile/* > ~/evidence/volatile/HASHES.txt

--- Disk Imaging ---

sudo dd if=/dev/sdb of=~/evidence/disk.img bs=4M status=progress conv=noerror,sync
sha256sum ~/evidence/disk.img > ~/evidence/disk.img.sha256
sudo mount -o ro,loop ~/evidence/disk.img /mnt/evidence


## Log Analysis Commands

# All failed logins
sudo grep "Failed password" /var/log/auth.log

# Top IPs brute-forcing SSH
sudo grep "Failed password" /var/log/auth.log | awk '{print $11}' | sort | uniq -c | sort -rn | head 20

# Successful logins only
sudo grep "Accepted" /var/log/auth.log

# All sudo commands run on the system
sudo grep "sudo" /var/log/auth.log

# Check if bash history was tampered with
echo $HISTFILE
cat ~/.bash_history


## Simulated Incident Lab

--- Attacker Role: Plant the artifacts ---

echo '#!/bin/bash
while true; do curl http://192.168.1.99/beacon; sleep 60; done' > /tmp/.hidden_backdoor.sh
chmod +x /tmp/.hidden_backdoor.sh
(crontab -l 2>/dev/null; echo "*/5 * * * * /tmp/.hidden_backdoor.sh") | crontab -
sudo useradd -m -s /bin/bash rogue_user

--- Responder Role: Find everything without being told where to look ---

find /tmp -name ".*" -type f
crontab -l
cat /etc/passwd | tail -10
ss -antp | grep ESTABLISHED

--- Eradication ---

rm /tmp/.hidden_backdoor.sh
crontab -r
sudo userdel -r rogue_user


